  "prompt": "What does \"natural causality\" mean?",
  "response": "\"Natural causality\" generally refers to the principle that events in the natural world occur as a result of certain causes based on the laws of nature. It implies that there is a consistent and predictable relationship between cause and effect within the natural environment. This concept is often contrasted with supernatural explanations, which rely on ideas or entities beyond the observable universe.\n\nIn philosophical discussions, natural causality is foundational to scientific inquiry, as it posits that natural phenomena can be understood through observation, experimentation, and reasoning. It underscores the idea that the universe operates according to specific, understandable laws, allowing us to infer cause-and-effect relationships. \n\nThe term can also be related to discussions in areas like philosophy of science, metaphysics, and epistemology, where the nature and implications of causality are explored in depth. Specifically, it can touch on topics such as determinism, free will, and the relationship between events and conditions in various natural sciences.",
